user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following init_response_body_data code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 21.17.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17 is Use of the string handling functions from <string.h> shall not result in accesses beyond the bounds of the objects referenced by their pointer parameters.
This rule strictly applies to the Standard Library functions in <string.h> such as memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, and strspn.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of init_response_body_data.
```c
static int
init_response_body_data (void)
{
  if (0 != body_dyn_size)
  {
    body_dyn = (char *) malloc (body_dyn_size);
    if (NULL == body_dyn)
    {
      fprintf (stderr, "Failed to allocate memory.\n");
      return 0;
    }
    if (tool_params.medium)
    {
      /* Fill the body with HTML-like content */
      size_t pos;
      size_t filler_pos;
      static const char body_header[] =
        "<html>\n"
        "<head>\n<title>Sample page title</title>\n<head>\n"
        "<body>\n";
      static const char body_filler[] =
        "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog.<br>\n";
      static const char body_footer[] =
        "</body>\n"
        "</html>\n";
      pos = 0;
      memcpy (body_dyn + pos, body_header, MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_header));
      pos += MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_header);
      for (filler_pos = 0;
           filler_pos < (body_dyn_size - (MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_header)
                                          + MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_footer)));
           ++filler_pos)
      {
        body_dyn[pos + filler_pos] =
          body_filler[filler_pos % MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_filler)];
      }
      pos += filler_pos;
      memcpy (body_dyn + pos, body_footer, MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_ (body_footer));
    }
    else
    {
      /* Fill the body with binary-like content */
      size_t pos;
      for (pos = 0; pos < body_dyn_size; ++pos)
      {
        body_dyn[pos] = (char) (unsigned char) (255U - pos % 256U);
      }
    }
  }
  return ! 0;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
The allocation itself does not directly call any <string.h> function, but the surrounding code can cause out-of-bounds accesses if the allocated size is too small. Specifically, if body_dyn_size is non‑zero but smaller than (MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_(body_header) + MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_(body_footer)), the expression

  body_dyn_size - (MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_(body_header) + MHD_STATICSTR_LEN_(body_footer))

underflows (size_t is unsigned) producing a very large loop bound. The subsequent writes in the filler loop and the final memcpy of the footer will then write beyond the body_dyn allocation, violating MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17. Thus there exists a feasible scenario (e.g. body_dyn_size > 0 but less than the combined header+footer length) where the string/memory functions access out of bounds.
</scenario>
